EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A storm system moved from the Great Lakes into New York State Sunday evening, May 27th. Associated rainfall saturated the soil and gusty winds resulted in a few trees down. Specifically, in Ogdensburg NY,  a tree was reported down on 2 different roads around  617 PM EST (717 PM EDT)...and a tree was leaning against a house around 650 PM EST (750 PM EDT).

column39: Primary storm system moved across southern Canada during Thursday, December 6th. Gusty winds occurred with passage of the associated cold front during the morning and early afternoon. A number of locations reported wind gusts over 34 mph (30 kts). A few wind gust reports included: In St Lawrence county, Canton with 46 mph (40 kts) while Massena had 44 mph (38 kts). In Clinton county, Plattsburgh had 39 mph (34 kts) while in Essex county Saranac Lake reported 37 mph (32 kts). In addition, scattered power outages were reported in Malone located in Franklin county.

A large low pressure system moved across the province of  Quebec late Tuesday and Tuesday night, February 4th into the early morning hours of February 5th. Winds were gusty during the day ahead of the low pressure system. However, following the associated cold front, winds were gusting to between 35 and 55 mph (30 and 48 knots) during the evening and night of February 4th. In St Lawrence county, a  peak  wind gust of 50 mph (43 knots) was noted at Massena , NY while 47 mph (41 knots) was reported at Canton, NY. In Franklin county, Saranac Lake reported 43 mph (37 knots).

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A significant warmup allowed the large winter ice buildup to begin breaking up on Lake George in Warren County during mid April.  A back door cold front, followed by a large high pressure area building south out of Canada, produced strong northeasterly winds, estimated in the 31 to 39 mph range on the afternoon of April 16. These winds pushed huge chunks of ice into the boat docks on the southern tip of Lake George, namely the village of Lake George. These chunks of ice caused extensive damage to at least four boat docks in this area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a cluster of heavy showers and thunderstorms moved across Rockland County, peak wind gusts estimated at 35 mph and heavy rain caused 1 large tree branch to fall on and injure 1 woman.

As Hurricane Isabel moved northwest toward the southern Mid Atlantic States, a strong high pressure system built over Northern New England.  As the pressure gradient increased, strong northeast winds developed across the region Thursday, September 18th.  Hurricane Isabel made landfall near Drum Inlet, North Carolina at 1 pm on the eighteenth. As Isabel accelerated toward the north northwest, tropical storm force winds rapidly expanded north.  Tropical storm force winds of 39 miles per hour (mph) occurred across parts of Nassau County, Queens, Brooklyn, and Staten Island from Thursday evening through Thursday night. Across Rockland, Westchester, and Suffolk Counties, east winds were sustained between 25 and 35 mph with peak gusts between 35 and 45 mph. When strong winds were accompanied by bands of heavy showers, many trees, tree limbs, and power lines were downed across the region.  The greatest damage occurred from Nassau County west across Staten Island. 

These strong winds resulted in 1 death and 2 injuries:

A 42 year old male police officer drowned while body surfing in high surf off Long Beach in Nassau County around 6 pm on the 18th.

A large tree limb fell through the driver's car door and speared a man while driving through Great Neck Estates at the Intersection of Bayview Ave. and Glenview Drive in Nassau County.  This resulted in a critical injury.

A 47 year old male was struck in the head by a fallen tree branch at the intersection of Andrews Ave. and University Ave. in the Bronx around 9 pm on the 18th.  This resulted in a serious head injury.

The New York City Department of Parks and Recreation provided this information:

In Queens, 259 trees were downed and 350 tree limbs were downed.
In Brooklyn, 197 trees were downed and 268 tree limbs were downed.
In Staten Island, 97 trees were downed and 74 tree limbs were downed.
In the Bronx, 54 trees were downed and 64 tree limbs were downed.
In Manhattan, 33 trees were downed and 45 tree limbs were downed.

Here are selected wind velocity measurements across the region:

In Queens, the Automated Surface Observing Systems at:

LaGuardia Airport measured a sustained 2 minute wind velocity of 40 mph from 120 degrees at 2:36 am EDT on the 19th with a peak gust to 51 mph from 120 degrees at 1:20 am EDT on the 19th.

JFK Airport measured a sustained 2 minute wind velocity of 40 mph from 100 degrees at 4:02 am EDT on the 19th with a peak gust to 49 mph from 80 degrees at 12:05 am on the 19th.

At the Ambrose Light C-MAN Station, the highest wind velocity measured at a height of 29 meters was a sustained 39 knot speed at 7 pm on the 18th with a peak gust to 44 knots.

In Nassau County, sustained wind speeds were measured at 10 pm EDT by an Automated Weather Station at 38 mph with a peak gust to 50 mph at Long Beach High School.  The Long Island Power Authority reported 41,599 power outages across Nassau County.

In Brooklyn, a peak wind gust to 47 mph was measured by an Automated Weather Station at the New Utrecht High School.  Three sides of a brick facade blew out along an exterior wall at Cinema World Studios in Green Point.

In Manhattan, a peak wind gust to 46 mph was measured by an Automated Weather Station at the Manhattan Center for Science and Math.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A non-thunderstorm wind gust caused a pine tree to fall through the roof of a house in Lake Huntington, in the town of Cochecton.  The white pine, 3 feet in diameter, broke several roof rafters and punched a hole in the bedroom window.   The owners, who were sleeping in that bedroom, were uninjured.

Strong gusty winds approaching 50 mph behind a cold front caused trees and wires to fall.  The strong wind caused a 10 foot high facade on a building in Bath to fall 15 feet to the ground.  The facade fell on a woman injuring her.  Debris continued to fall during her rescue injuring a man helping her.  Also in Bath a 20 foot metal flagpole was bent.  In Avoca, a tree ignited when it fell on a utility pole.
Strong winds with gusts approaching 50 mph caused isolated damage in Watkins Glen.  After an electric  substation was damaged, more than 1000 customers were without power.

Strong winds downed a tree onto a car traveling south along the Cross Island Parkway near the Grand Central Parkway in Queens.  The tree crushed the driver to death.  Peak wind gusts were measured at 47 mph at LaGuardia Airport and 45 mph at Kennedy Airport.

As a shower moved east across the area, it produced a peak wind gust to 36 mph at Central Park.  Two injuries resulted.  A pedestrian was struck by a table blown off a roof 2 miles east of Central Park.  A man was struck by debris blown off a roof 1 mile east of Central Park.

A storm system moved rapidly across the Province of Quebec on the 29th of September. The associated cold front moved across northern New York during the morning of September 29th. The front was accompanied by showers and thunderstorms. Large scale strong and gusty winds preceded and followed the front. Winds were generally estimated at a sustained 35 mph with higher gusts. A few tree limbs were blown down.

A strong west pressure gradient developed as an intensifying low pressure system moved north across Northern New England as a ridge of high pressure extended south across the Western Great Lakes.  With very wet antecedent conditions and most trees with full leaf canopies, many trees were downed in saturated ground as peak west winds gusted from 36 to 46 mph.

An off duty NWS employee reported a tree down on a house in Hampton Bays.  The NYC Office of Emergency Management reported trees down at many locations throughout Staten Island, Brooklyn, and Queens.  They also reported that a window on the 17th floor at Seventh Avenue and Forty Ninth Street in Manhattan was blown out as glass shattered in the streets.  A tree fell on a moving car on Jackie Robinson Parkway in Flushing Queens.  Injuries were unknown.  A tree fell on a person in Clove Lakes Park, about 1 mile north of Todt Hill in Staten Island.  Injury was unknown.

A low pressure system moved across northern portions of Ontario Province early on the 29th of November, and into Quebec Province by the afternoon of the 29th of November. Gusty south winds preceded the associated cold front during the morning and early afternoon hours of November 29th. In the Saranac Lake area of southern Franklin county New York, power lines were blown down on top of a vehicle which resulted in a brief road closure.

A powerful storm tracked northeast across the northern Great Lakes on the 17th and across Ontario and Quebec provinces on the 18th. Preceding this storm, during the morning of the 18th, brisk south to southeast winds of 20 to 30 mph with gusts exceeding 40 mph were common across much of the region. After the cold frontal passage during midday, west to southwest winds of equal speeds continued. Saranac Lake reported a wind gust of 40 mph.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong area of low pressure moved from the Great Lakes across southern Quebec province Canada during the late morning and afternoon of the 24th, accompanied by a cold front.  The combination of a tight pressure gradient and the arrival of colder air behind the cold front created strong winds with gusts up to 50 mph during the late morning and afternoon. There were several reports of small trees, branches and powerlines down in Clinton, Essex, Franklin and St. Lawrence counties that resulted in power outages and isolated structural damage. Some specific communities affected included Chazy (Clinton), Altona (Clinton), Keeseville (Essex), Scotia (Clinton),  Black Brook (Clinton), Morrisonville (Clinton) and Duane (Franklin), where a tree limb fell on a house and caused some minor roof damage. Some observed wind gusts included 49 mph at Fort Covington (Franklin), 45 mph at Saranac Lake (Franklin), 44 mph at Massena (St. Lawrence) and 41 mph at Plattsburgh (Clinton).

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong northwest winds resulted in 1 injury in Midtown Manhattan.  Metal blew off a construction scaffold and injured a pedestrian near the intersection of 1st Avenue and East 82nd Street.  Glass blew off a building under construction near the intersection of West 40th and 8th Avenues.  A 20 by 10 foot billboard blew down into a parking lot near Remsen and Ave A in Brooklyn.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a low pressure system moved northeast across Southeast Canada, a high pressure system built southeast across the Ohio Valley.  This resulted in a strong northwest pressure gradient that caused winds to gust to 47 mph at JFK Airport and to 46 mph at Westchester County Airport and in Lindenhurst.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: An apparent dry microburst was associated with the trough's passage at around 3:15 pm in Lindenhurst NY, damaging car windows at an auto dealership, and blowing away segments of fencing at the dealership and a near by IHOP.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A trough of low pressure moved through Long Island the afternoon of March 3rd, bringing scattered showers with it. An apparent dry microburst was associated with the trough's passage at around 3:15 pm in Lindenhurst NY.

A strong and rapidly intensifying low pressure system moved from the Great Lakes across Ontario and western Quebec during the morning and early afternoon of January 9th. A very strong low-level wind field with southwest winds in excess of 70 mph just above the surface moved across northern New York during the late morning and early afternoon hours. ||Some of these strong winds translated down to the surface and caused scattered wind damage in the form of downed trees and scattered power outages across eastern Clinton and eastern Essex counties in New York.|Some recorded wind gusts included; 49 mph in Beekmantown, 46 mph in Peru and 45 mph at Plattsburgh (Clinton county).

A powerful winter storm moved from the lower Mississippi River Valley on the morning of March 4th, into the Ohio River Valley during the night and then across New England on the 5th.||Strong winds associated with this storm gusted to near 50 mph in portions of the Adirondacks and combined with accumulated ice on trees that resulted in scattered downed tree branches, limbs and power outages.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree reportedly fell onto a home in Altamont, along with wires. The downed tree and wires was the result of strong winds.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A rapidly strengthening low pressure system tracked from the central Gulf Coast on Friday March 7th, to the central Appalachians by Saturday morning on March 8th, and reached northern Maine by Sunday morning March 9th.||As cold air to the north of the storm system filtered southward, precipitation in the form of snow, sleet and rain developed late Friday. The precipitation then changed to freezing rain by Saturday morning, which then persisted, heavily at times, into Saturday evening before changing back to light snow.||Significant ice accumulations in excess of one inch occurred from this storm. In addition, gusty winds developed Saturday afternoon. This combination led to widespread power outages and downed trees, with the areas of Hague, Johnsburg, and Queensbury the hardest hit. In these regions, more than 100 power poles were downed, with more than 300 sections of wire also pulled down. In addition, over 1000 trees were estimated to have fallen from the extreme ice accretion.||The large number of downed trees and wires led to numerous road closures, including Route 8, and Route 9N in and near Hague.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree fell on a moving car traveling south on Furnace Dock Road, in Cortlandt Westchester County, killing the driver and casing minor injuries to 2 passengers.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds on the backside of a vigorous Low over Southeast Canada downed a tree on a car in Westchester County, killing 1 person and injuring 2 others.

During the evening of April 1st into the early morning hours of April 2nd, strong winds of 25 to 35 mph with gusts to 50 mph blew across northern New York. This was a result of a combination of strong high pressure off the Atlantic coast along with a strong and deepening area of low pressure that moved across the Great Lakes and southeast Canada. These strong winds knocked down a few tree limbs and caused scattered power outages.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The remnants of tropical cyclone Hanna, interacted with an approaching cold front from the west, leading to widespread heavy rainfall across the mid Hudson Valley of eastern New York and southwest New England during Saturday September 6th, and ending by early Sunday morning on September 7th. Rainfall amounts of 3 to 6 inches fell across this region, leading to some flooding.||In addition, gusty winds occurred across portions of the region.

Measured wind gusts of 45 to 55 mph were recorded, leading to numerous downed trees, tree limbs and power lines across the affected area.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong cold front swept east across the region during the evening hours of Saturday October 25th. A wave of low pressure developed along this front and lifted north during the evening, creating locally heavy rainfall across portions of eastern New York and western New England.||In addition, the tight pressure gradient between the approaching front, and strong high pressure off the New England coast, created gusty southeast to south winds across the region from Saturday afternoon into the evening, which led to some downed trees, tree limbs and power lines.

A powerful storm moved from the Mississippi River Valley on December 24th across the Great Lakes and into eastern Quebec by the morning of December 25th. A strong cold front associated with this storm moved across northern New York during the late evening. South to southwest winds of 20 to 30 mph with gusts to 40 mph ahead of the cold front shifted to the west-northwest at 25 to 35 mph with gusts to 50 mph during early Christmas morning. Scattered reports of tree limbs, power outages and torn roof shingles were reported.

A low pressure system tracked from the Great Lakes on Wednesday December 24th, to off the northern New England coast by Thursday morning on December 25th.||Strong winds developed immediately ahead of, and with a cold frontal passage Wednesday night, and persisted into Thursday morning. Wind gusts of 40 to 50 mph occurred, with the strongest winds extending from the immediate Capital District extending into the Mohawk Valley and southern Adirondacks.

A tight pressure gradient between a strong low pressure system over northern New England, and an approaching ridge of high pressure from the west, led to strong winds across eastern New York and western New England, from Monday evening, into midday Tuesday.||Wind gusts of 45 to 55 mph occurred, resulting in scattered power outages and downed trees and tree limbs. Approximately 7200 customers were without power in eastern New York State, mostly across northern portions of the Capital region, into Saratoga County.

An intensifying area of low pressure in the Central Plains on March 10th, tracked across the Northern Great Lakes and into Hudson Bay on March 11th.  Meanwhile, an area of surface high pressure was located  across Eastern Canada and this allowed for a strong pressure gradient across New York.||A strong low-level jet aloft preceded an approaching cold front on  March 11th and eventually lowered to the surface during the afternoon. Surface winds of 25 to 35 mph with gusts in excess of 50 mph were observed with scattered tree damage and very isolated property damage.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A tree was reported down at the intersection of Moe Road and Englemore Road in Clifton Park.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strengthening low pressure system tracked northeast from the southern Plains on Thursday April 2nd, to the upper Ohio Valley by Friday morning April 3rd, and into southern Quebec by Saturday morning April 4th.||The tightening pressure gradient around this low pressure system led to strong gusty winds across portions of eastern New York and western New England during Saturday. Peak wind gusts of 35 to 45 MPH were measured across the region.

An unseasonably strong spring storm moved across the northern Plains into central Canada on May 13th and 14th. At the same time, a strong surface high was located across New England on May 13th and strengthened while it slowly exited south of Nova Scotia on May 14th. This created a strong pressure gradient across northern New York. In addition, a strong mid-level disturbance moved across the Great Lakes and through northern New York and Vermont on the 14th.||Strong south to southwest winds of 25 to 35 mph with frequent gusts in excess of 50 mph was witnessed across much of northern New York during the morning and early afternoon hours of May 14th. These winds resulted in numerous reports of scattered downed trees, as the spring season accounted for foliage on the trees. There were some localized higher gusts that approached 60 mph that caused some minor structural damage (roof shingles and poorly structured porches), as well as more numerous tree damage in portions of Franklin and western Clinton counties.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two large trees were reported down in Clifton Park as a result of strong winds.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A tight pressure gradient between high pressure off the New England coast, and a low pressure system located north of the Great Lakes, produced strong south to southeast winds across portions of eastern New York from late Thursday morning on May 14th, until the mid afternoon hours. A cold front associated with the low then crossed the region during the late afternoon hours, ending the strong winds.||Measured wind gusts were generally between 35 and 50 mph across the immediate Hudson River Valley from Albany northward, as well as across the Mohawk Valley and southwest Adirondacks. However, locally stronger gusts were estimated in portions of southern Herkimer County, where numerous trees and wires were downed.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were reported down in Guilderland due to strong winds. Additional trees were also reported down in the City of Albany.||A peak wind gust of 49 mph was recorded at the National Weather Service Office in Albany, while 44 mph was recorded at the Albany International Airport.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A tight pressure gradient between high pressure off the New England coast, and a low pressure system located north of the Great Lakes, produced strong south to southeast winds across portions of eastern New York from late Thursday morning on May 14th, until the mid afternoon hours. A cold front associated with the low then crossed the region during the late afternoon hours, ending the strong winds.||Measured wind gusts were generally between 35 and 50 mph across the immediate Hudson River Valley from Albany northward, as well as across the Mohawk Valley and southwest Adirondacks. However, locally stronger gusts were estimated in portions of southern Herkimer County, where numerous trees and wires were downed.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Trees and wires were reported down and blocking State Route 40 from Bracken Road into the town of Schaghticoke, as a result of strong winds. In addition, power lines were reported down near Brunswick Center, on Route 7 between Carrolls Grove Road and Brick Church Road.

A vigorous and unseasonably cold storm system traversed across Ontario and Quebec provinces on May 31st. This translated into a strong mid-level disturbance and low-level jet stream that supported a sharp, strong cold front. ||This strong cold front moved across northern New York during the afternoon and resulted in a brief period of strong and gusty winds of 40 to 50 mph along with a 20 degree temperature plunge. These strong winds accounted for numerous reports of fallen trees and scattered power outages. There were numerous reports of pea-size hail across northern New York and several reports of light snow in the Adirondacks.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: The passage of a strong upper level disturbance allowed strong wind gusts to develop across portions of the southern Adirondacks and Schoharie Valley during Sunday afternoon May 31st. Wind gusts of 35 to 45 mph were observed, and resulted in some downed trees and power lines.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A downed tree was reportedly blocking Charlotte Valley Road between Mooney Road and Grady Road in Charlotteville due to strong winds.

EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A deep area of low pressure moved east across the Great Lakes, and brought a strong cold front eastward across central New York during the early morning hours. Isolated thunderstorms associated with the cold front caused scattered wind damage across the area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds downed trees and tree limbs and caused scattered power outages.  Around 11 am EDT, police said that a tree fell on a moving car travelling west on Route 17A in Warwick.  A man and woman suffered minor injuries when their car overturned.  Orange and Rockland Utilities reported power outages in the town of Tuxedo.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Following the passage of a strong cold front, strong west winds developed.  Peak gusts ranged from around 45 mph to 55 mph and caused scattered power outages.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tree reported down on a car at Route 9 and Alpine Drive in Wappingers Falls due to strong winds. Also, trees and wires were reported down around East Fishkill.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds downed a tree branch on a woman in the Bronx, who was taken to a hospital after receiving a minor injury to her head.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds combined with heavy rain downed numerous trees and power lines across Orange County causing around a thousand power outages.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds developed between a deep low pressure system northeast of Maine and a strong high pressure system over the Southeast United States.  Peak wind gusts ranged from 40 mph to 55 mph.  They downed tree limbs and caused scattered power outages across Southeast NY.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds combined with heavy rain downed numerous trees and power lines across Rockland County causing around a thousand power outages.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds developed between a deep low pressure system northeast of Maine and a strong high pressure system over the Southeast United States.  Peak wind gusts ranged from 40 mph to 55 mph.  They downed tree limbs and caused scattered power outages across Southeast NY.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A peak wind gust of 44 mph was measured by a mesonet station in Huntington Station.  Law enforcement reported downed tree limbs and trees in Fort Salonga and Stony Brook.  A tree fell on and damaged a pickup truck in Stony Brook.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Strong winds developed between a deep low pressure system northeast of Maine and a strong high pressure system over the Southeast United States.  Peak wind gusts ranged from 40 mph to 55 mph.  They downed tree limbs and caused scattered power outages across Southeast NY.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong northwest winds behind deep low pressure over the western Atlantic Ocean ripped scores of bricks from a building on Pacific Steet in Brooklyn NY.  No one was injured.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Deep low pressure over the western Atlantic Ocean resulted in a prolonged period of strong northwest winds.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Sidewalk bridging along Alcott Place collapsed, injuring one person.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were downed due to strong winds.  A tree fell on Portion Road between Morris Ave. and Maple Crest Drive in Farmingville.  A large tree was down at the intersection of Pine St. and Wilson Blvd. in Islip.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous trees were downed near Riverhead due to strong winds.  A large tree was downed on Ackerly Pond Lane in Southold.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A large tree fell between two homes at the corner of Park Place and Albertson Street in Hyde Park. The tree hit an overhang on one house. Another tree fell on a house and car on White Oaks Road in Hyde Park causing major structural damage to the house.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure developed along the southeast coast Monday, March 29th, and strengthened as it moved gradually northward. The storm reached its peak intensity Tuesday morning and stalled just south of Long Island. During the day Tuesday the low began to weaken and move very slowly eastward. The storm tapped into abundant moisture which resulted in a heavy rainfall of 1 1/2 to 3 inches across Schoharie County.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Tree limbs, approximately 6 inches in diameter, were reported down on power lines across Grassville Road in Brant Lake.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Much above normal temperatures during early April resulted in an early start to the growing season across portions of east central New York. ||With clearing skies, diminishing winds and an unseasonably cold airmass in place, temperatures fell into the upper 20s to lower 30s during the early morning hours of Thursday, April 29th across portions of east central New York, including Columbia, eastern Rensselaer, southern Washington, northern Saratoga, southeastern Warren and southern Fulton counties.||In addition, the combination of a tight pressure gradient, and the passage of a strong upper level atmospheric disturbance resulted in strong and gusty winds during Thursday, with some gusts approaching 50 mph.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds knocked down numerous trees across Queens County during the afternoon and evening. Flushing, Queensboro Hill, College Point, Malba, Whitestone and Bay Terrace were among the locations where trees were reported downed. Power outages occurred and a tree fell onto a car on College Point Blvd. at 25th Avenue.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: An area of low pressure moved to the north dragging a cold front through on May 8th 2010. The pressure gradient tightened considerably behind this front as the low moved to the northeast of the area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Two people were injured when gusty winds brought a tree limb down on a car.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Gusty winds were mixed down to the surface behind a strong cold frontal passage.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Large branches and power lines were reported down in Ozone Park, in Queens. One of the branches landed on a car.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A developing coastal storm off of Long Island created strong winds and heavy rains, which were sufficient to bring down large branches and power lines in Queens.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Strong winds were responsible for the loss of power to approximately 1,800 customers in Nassau and western Suffolk Counties due to downed power lines and trees.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust to 47 mph was measured at Shinnecock Hills at 9:49 am.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system approached from the south and caused strong wind gusts ranging from around 40 to 55 mph across the area.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous reports of large branches and several shallow-rooted trees downed by prolonged north winds of 25 to 35 mph with frequent gusts around 50 mph across saturated soils. Lake Champlain Ferries were closed due to strong winds and excessive waves.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: Low pressure off the Delmarva Peninsula on October 14th intensified rapidly into a strong Nor'easter as it moved across southeast Massachusetts into the Gulf of Maine on the 15th. There were three components to this storm...heavy rainfall, first snowfall of the season in the higher elevations and strong winds.||Strong north winds of 20 to 30 mph with gusts approaching 50 mph battered the Champlain Valley for much of the late morning and afternoon hours of October 15th. This caused scattered damage to trees and tree limbs with isolated to scattered power outages. It also caused the ferries between Vermont and New York to shut down operations for several hours.||In addition, rainfall totals across the Champlain Valley ranged from 1.5 to 4 inches with minor street and small stream flooding. Snowfall was largely confined to elevations above 2000 feet with 3 to 7 inches being reported.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust to 50 mph was measured in Bayville at 2:48 pm.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system moved across the region and passed to the northeast.  It produced wind gusts from around 40 to 50 mph.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust to 50 mph was measured at Shinnecock Hills at 8:29 pm.  Shirley Airport measured a wind gust to 46 mph, as did Napeague during the late morning and early afternoon.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system moved across the region and passed to the northeast.  It produced wind gusts from around 40 to 50 mph.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: A wind gust to 50 mph was measured at Great Gull Island at 8:13 pm.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A strong low pressure system moved across the region and passed to the northeast.  It produced wind gusts from around 40 to 50 mph.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Based on a news story from the Daily News:  FIERCE winds ripped a 20-foot-long branch from aa tree in Brooklyn, sending it plunging to the ground where it struck and critically injured a young woman.  The branch fell from East Seventh street just after 2 pm.||Peak wind gusts of 52 mph was measured at John F. Kennedy Airport, 51 mph at La Guardia Airport, 48 mph at Farmingdale Airport, and 47 mph at Bayville.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: As a strong cold front moved east of the area, strong northwest winds developed.  Peak wind gusts ranged from around 40 to 55 mph.

EVENT_NARRATIVE: Numerous tree branches and limbs downed by persistent and strong winds of 20 to 30 mph with gusts to 55 mph. Scattered to numerous power outages reported as well as some structural and vehicle damage due to fallen trees.
EPISODE_NARRATIVE: A massive and powerful storm system (990mb) moved from the northern Great Lakes on November 30th across Ontario into James Bay Canada on December 1st. An associated cold front slowly moved east across the Great Lakes toward New York and New England with development of several waves of low pressure. Meanwhile, a very strong area of high pressure (1032mb) was located across New Brunswick. The large pressure gradient (> 40mb) between both systems resulted in very strong south to southeast winds in a return flow. Very strong wind dynamics at all levels in the atmosphere resulted in fierce low-level winds in excess of 100 mph just 5000 feet above the surface.||Some of these winds eventually transitioned across the higher peaks of the Adirondacks and caused strong down slope winds on the northern slopes of the Adirondacks as well as some strong funneling winds in the Champlain Valley. South to southeast winds of 20 to 30 mph with wind gusts approaching 50 mph occurred for a prolonged duration from pre-dawn to the early afternoon hours. Some of the measured wind gusts included; 54 mph in Ellenburg (Clinton county), 52 mph in Malone (Franklin county), 51 mph in Saranac Lake (Franklin county) with 47 mph in Potsdam (St. Lawrence county) and 43 mph at Massena (St. Lawrence county).||The persistent strength and duration of this wind event accounted for numerous reports of limbs, branches and some trees downed by the wind that resulted in scattered to numerous power outages (more than 5000 utility customers) and some minor structural damage as a result of fallen debris.
